Certainly! Below is an example of a two-player zero-sum game using TikZ in LaTeX. This example includes diamond nodes representing the algorithm player's decisions and filled circle nodes representing the adversary player's decisions. The edges between these nodes represent the payoffs.

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm,
        decision/.style={diamond, draw, fill=blue!30, text width=4em, text badly centered, node distance=3cm, inner sep=0pt},
        action/.style={circle, draw, fill=red!30, text width=3em, text centered, minimum size=1em}]

        % Nodes
        \node [decision] (A) {Algorithm};
        \node [action, below left of=A] (AS) {S};
        \node [action, below right of=A] (AC) {C};

        % Edges with labels
        \draw [->] (A) -- node[anchor=east] {$-5$} (AS);
        \draw [->] (A) -- node[anchor=west] {$-2$} (AC);

        % Adversary nodes
        \node [action, below left of=AS] (SS) {S};
        \node [action, below right of=AS] (SC) {C};
        \node [action, below left of=AC] (CS) {S};
        \node [action, below right of=AC] (CC) {C};

        % Edge labels
        \draw [->] (AS) -- node[anchor=north] {$2$} (SS);
        \draw [->] (AS) -- node[anchor=south] {$1$} (SC);
        \draw [->] (AC) -- node[anchor=north] {$3$} (CS);
        \draw [->] (AC) -- node[anchor=south] {$0$} (CC);
    \end{tikzpicture}
    \caption{Two-Player Zero-Sum Game Example}
    \label{fig:zero_sum_game}
\end{figure}

\end{document}
```

